\begin{align*}
 { \frac { { I_ { max } } - I }  { { I_ { max } } } } = { \rm { } } { \frac { { \frac { { N_ { \left. { 0 ( Max1 } \right) } } }  { { N_0 } } } }  { 1 + { { \left( { { \frac { I { C_ { \left. { 50 ( 1 } \right) } } }  { \left[ { Z { n^ { 2 + } } } \right] } } } \right) } ^ { nH } } } } + { \rm { } } { \frac { { \frac { { N_ { \left. { 0 ( Max2 } \right) } } }  { { N_0 } } } }  { 1 + { { \left( { { \frac { I { C_ { \left. { 50 ( 2 } \right) } } }  { \left[ { Z { n^ { 2 + } } } \right] } } } \right) } ^ { nH } } } } ,
\end{align*}
\end{document}

where N0 is the total amount of zinc-binding sites, N0(max1) is the amount of high-affinity binding sites, N0(max2) is the amount of low-affinity binding sites, Imax is the maximal CaV3.2 peak current amplitude, IC50 is the [Zn2+] necessary for half-maximal inhibition, and nH is the Hill coefficient. The concentration dependency of the S9SP effect was fit to the one-component logistic function:
